nema -- tCarl Dreyer's The Passion of Joan of Arc -- tThe Comic in Cinema -- tBuñuel as Therorist -- tThe Cinematic Shot -- tDécoupage, or Cinematic Segmentation -- tCinema as an Instrument of Poetry -- tBuñuel as Scriptwriter -- tGoya and the Duchess of Alba -- tUn Chien andalou -- tL'Age d'or -- tGags -- tHallucinations about a Dead Hand -- tIllegible, the Son of a Flute -- tAgon (Swansong) -- tBuñuel as Buñuel -- tLand without Bread -- tViridiana -- tTo PECIME (Asociación de periodistas cinematográficos y de espectáculos de México) -- tAutobiographical Writings -- tFragments of a Journal from Buñuel's Youth in Calanda -- tMedieval Memories of Lower Aragón -- tFrom Buñuel's Autobiography -- tPessimism -- tAfterword0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough Luis Buñuel, one of the great filmmakers of the century, was notoriously reluctant to discuss his own work in public, he wrote--and wrote well--on many subjects over the years. This collection proceeds chronologically, from poetry and short stories written in Buñuel's youth in Spain to an essay written in 1980, not long before his death. Newly translated into English, the writings offer startling insights into the filmmaker's life and thought. The earliest pieces came well before Buñuel joined the Surrealist movement in Paris and created the landmark film Un chien andalou with Salvador Dalí. Yet these and the early Surrealist writings reveal the inventiveness of the mind that would later create such masterpieces of cinema as L'Age d'or, Los olvidados, Viridiana, The Milky Way, The Discreet Charm of the Bourgeoisie, and That Obscure Object of Desire. Later writings, which include screenplays and reflections on his own and others' films, illuminate many aspects of Buñuel's career, as well as the ways of thinking and perceiving that underlie his unique cinematic style. The final essay by this extraordinary artist sums up his view of the world--still vibrant and full of contradictions--at the end of his life.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aFilm. 4aGeneral. 4aPerforming Arts. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh1 aBuñuel, Juan Luis , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuñuel, Juan Luis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuñuel, Luis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuñuel, Rafael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarriere, Jean-Claude, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarrière, Jean-Claude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWhite, Garrett, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023423940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052035439540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520354395423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520354395/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles